The prime factorization of 9! is $2^7 \times 3^4 \times 5^1 \times 7^1$.
The number of divisors of a number $n = p_1^{a_1} p_2^{a_2} \dots p_k^{a_k}$ is given by $(a_1+1)(a_2+1)\dots(a_k+1)$.
In this case, the number of divisors of 9! is $(7+1)(4+1)(1+1)(1+1) = (8)(5)(2)(2) = 160$.

ground_truth:

\[2^7 \cdot 3^4 \cdot 5 \cdot 7,\]so from the formula for the number of factors of a number, the number of factors of 9! is $(7+1)(4+1)(1+1)(1+1) = \boxed{160}.$
